:"1275年–1335年","1260–1345":"1260年–1345年","1292–1341":"1292年–1341年","1301–Male":"1301年–殁","1260–1305":"1260年–1305年","1260–1342":"1260年–1342年","1305":"1305年","about 1292":"大约1292年","1335":"1335年","1301":"1301年","1345":"1345年","about 1290":"大约1290年","1342":"1342年","1341":"1341年","1275":"1275年","about 1275":"大约1275年","1260":"1260年","1292":"1292年","Scotland":"苏格兰","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"英国英格兰肯特史崔特","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"苏格兰培爾斯特拉洛","lifeSummary":"当Isabel Comyn于大约1275年出生在苏格兰时，她的父亲Alasdair Comyn16岁，母亲Joan de LATIMER16岁。她于大约1290年与Freskin Francis Cheyne在苏格兰结婚。他们至少是1个儿子和1个女儿的父母。她去世于1335年在她的家乡享年61岁，埋葬在苏格兰。"},"hr":{"about 1275–1335":"oko 1275.–1335.","1275–1335":"1275–1335.","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301.–preminuo","1260–1305":"1260–1305.","1260–1342":"1260–1342","1305":"1305.","about 1292":"oko 1292.","1335":"1335.","1301":"1301.","1345":"1345","about 1290":"oko 1290.","1342":"1342","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","about 1275":"oko 1275.","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","Scotland":"Scotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, Engleska, United Kingdom","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland"},"cs":{"about 1275–1335":"okolo 1275–1335","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Zesnulý","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1260–1342":"1260–1342","1305":"1305","about 1292":"okolo 1292","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","about 1290":"okolo 1290","1342":"1342","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","about 1275":"okolo 1275","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","Scotland":"Scotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, Anglie, United Kingdom","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland"},"da":{"about 1275–1335":"omkring 1275–1335","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Afdød","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1260–1342":"1260–1342","1305":"1305","about 1292":"omkring 1292","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","about 1290":"omkring 1290","1342":"1342","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","about 1275":"omkring 1275","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","Scotland":"Skotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Straloch, Perthshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"about 1275–1335":"circa 1275–1335","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Overleden","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1260–1342":"1260–1342","1305":"1305","about 1292":"circa 1292","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","about 1290":"circa 1290","1342":"1342","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","about 1275":"circa 1275","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","Scotland":"Schotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Straloch, Perthshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1275–1335":"about 1275–1335","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Deceased","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1260–1342":"1260–1342","1305":"1305","about 1292":"about 1292","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","about 1290":"about 1290","1342":"1342","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","about 1275":"about 1275","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","Scotland":"Scotland","New Street, Spring Gardens, England":"Street, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Comyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Irish:  see  Cumming  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cumming","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): most probably a habitational name from Bosc-Benard-Commin in Eure, France. This place lies on the edge of the Forêt de Rouvray, near Rouen, in the heart of the district from which came numerous Domesday barons, and so is much more likely to be the source of the name than Comines in Nord. The name is also possibly derived from the personal name <i>Cumin</i>, which is found in Norfolk, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th and 13th centuries and may be of Breton origin, according to Reaney. Compare Old Breton <i>Cunmin</i>, which also appears as <i>Cumin</i>, and is from <i>con-</i> ‘hound’ with an uncertain second element, perhaps the <i>min</i> ‘edge’ which is found in other personal names.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cuimín</b> (or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>) ‘son (or ‘descendant’) of <i>Cuimín</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>cam</i> ‘crooked’. There was a 7th-century abbot of Iona named <i>Cumin</i>. In Scotland, this Irish surname became confused with the Norman name.","History: A notable bearer of the Norman surname is Wilhelmus Comyn, Bishop of Durham, who came north to Scotland with King David I in 1124 and was appointed Chancellor of Scotland. He established his nephew Richard in Tynedale and Roxburghshire, and Richard also rose to be Chancellor of Scotland. The Comyn or Cumming family gained the earldoms of Buchan and Menteith and rose to be the most powerful noble family in Scotland in the century before the rise of King Robert Bruce."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Comyn was born about 1275, in Scotland, her father, Alasdair Comyn, was 16 and her mother, Joan de LATIMER, was 16. She married Freskin Francis Cheyne about 1290, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1335, in her hometown, at the age of 61, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"about 1275–1335":"umbes 1275–1335","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Surnud","1260–1305":"1260–1305","1260–1342":"1260–1342","1305":"1305","about 129